When docker gets installed, the file system gets generated in this structure:
/var/lib/docker, under this folder there are 4 folders:
/aufs
/containers
/image
/volumes

image layer is read only which includes source code, container layer is read and write, so if we want to update source code, the way it works is 
to update a file which is stored in image layer and keep the updated file in container layer, so if we delete a container, the updated file will be deleted as well.
to keep the updated files, we add a persistent volume.

When a container is destroyed, we probably want to store the data, data persistence is the process of storing data on non-volatile storage (like hard drives, SSDs, 
or databases) so it survives system reboots, power outages, or application termination.
To keep the data in the container, we can add a persistent volume to the container.
$ docker volume create data_volume  //it creates a folder data_volume under /var/lib/docker
$ docker run -v data_volume:/var/lib/mysql <image-name>  //it creates a new container and mounts the volume inside the docker containers


difference of storage driver and volumes in docker:
storage drivers manage how image and container layers are built on the host's filesystem, while volumes are dedicated mechanisms for persisting 
and sharing data outside of those layers.
